  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've witnessed firsthand through my own experiences and the stories of my neighbors. When I was in high school, I remember sitting in a science class where the teacher said, 'You're not cut out for this,' and it made me question my abilities even though I had always excelled in math. That moment, when a stereotype about one's group's capability becomes a self-fulfilling prophecy, is what stereotype threat really is. It's not about being 'less smart' but about the anxiety of being labeled as such. In Kansas City, where I've worked as a waitress for over thirty years, I've seen how this fear can affect people from all walks of life—not just students but professionals too. The stereotype threat in STEM is real, and it needs to be addressed because it prevents talented individuals from reaching their full potential. I believe we should address it by creating inclusive environments where everyone feels valued, not just the ones who fit the 'typical' mold. Schools and workplaces should provide mentorship programs that help students and professionals navigate these anxieties. It's not about changing the stereotypes themselves but about helping people understand that their worth isn't defined by a single subject or a single test score. In my own life, I've learned that kindness and patience can bridge gaps that stereotypes create. So, yes, we absolutely should address stereotype threat in STEM—it's time to make sure everyone has the chance to shine, regardless of their background.",
